.TH _PRINTF 3 "27 November 2025" "version 1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
_printf \- simplified formatted output function (educational)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
#include "main.h"
int _printf(const char *format, ...);
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
\fB_printf\fR is a small educational reimplementation of the standard
C library function \fBprintf(3)\fR. It parses a format string and writes
formatted output to standard output. This implementation intentionally
supports a limited subset of conversion specifiers; behaviour for other
features of the full `printf` (flags, field width, precision, length
modifiers) is not provided.

.SH CONVERSION SPECIFIERS
The following conversion specifiers are supported by this implementation:
.TP
\fI%c\fR
Print a single character. The corresponding argument is converted to
\fIunsigned char\fR and printed.
.TP
\fI%s\fR
Print a NUL-terminated string. If a NULL pointer is supplied the
implementation writes the 6-character string `(null)`.
.
.TP
\fI%d, %i\fR
Print a signed decimal integer. Negative values are printed with a
leading `-`. `INT_MIN` is handled specially to avoid overflow when
negating it.

.TP
\fI%%\fR
Print a literal percent sign.

.SH RETURN VALUE
On success, \fB_printf\fR returns the number of bytes written to
standard output. On error (for example, when \fIformat\fR is NULL, or
when the format string ends with an unmatched `%' character) the
function returns \fB-1\fR.

.SH ERRORS
This implementation does not set \fIerrno\fR for formatting errors.
Invalid or unsupported conversion sequences are printed as a percent
sign followed by the unknown character (for example, `"%q"` prints
`%q`). If the format string ends with a single `%' (no conversion
character after it), `_printf` returns `-1`.

.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
.B Character
.nf
_printf("I'm the letter: %c\n", 'A');
/* Output: I'm the letter: A */
.fi
.PP
.B String
.nf
_printf("I'm a %s!\n", "string");
/* Output: I'm a string! */
.fi
.PP
.B Percent sign
.nf
_printf("Progress: 100%%\n");
/* Output: Progress: 100% */
.fi
.PP
.B Integer
.nf
_printf("Number: %d\n", 123);
/* Output: Number: 123 */
.fi
.PP
.B NULL string handling
.nf
_printf("Null: %s\n", NULL);
/* Output: Null: (null) */
.fi
.PP
.B Unknown specifier
.nf
_printf("Unknown: %q\n");
/* Output: Unknown: %q */
.fi

.SH IMPLEMENTATION NOTES
.IP \(bu 2
This project uses a small dispatch table (`printer array`) mapping
conversion characters to handler functions. Handler function prototypes
are declared in `main.h`.
.IP \(bu 2
Variadic arguments are accessed with `stdarg.h` macros (`va_start`,
`va_arg`, `va_end`).
.IP \(bu 2
A helper `_putchar` wraps the `write` system call to emit one character
to standard output (see `_putchar.c`).

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR printf (3)
